                <note rend="inline" type="source">660H.1115/29: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Yugoslavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-23T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 23, 1939—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:14 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>321. My 184, July 6.<note n="25" xml:id="d867fn25">Not printed.</note> Minister
                    of Finance Šutej<note n="26" xml:id="d867fn26">Juraj Šutej replaced Vojin
                        Djuričić as Minister of Finance following the latter’s resignation August
                        24, 1939.</note> said to me this morning that in accordance with
                    instructions which he received from the Prince Regent he wished to recommence
                    negotiation for the granting of credit $500,000 from the Export-Import Bank for
                    the purchase of cotton. He said he would instruct Yugoslav Minister at
                    Washington to negotiate. Minister for Foreign Affairs subsequently confirmed the
                    foregoing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
